      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 45-year-old farmer comes to the clinic reporting chronic diarrhea and the development of dry, scaly skin lesions around his neck over the last three months. He has an erratic dietary pattern but consumes large amounts of jowar (sorghum), his primary crop, and has done so for over a decade and a half. Based on his diet and symptoms, which enzyme's inhibition is most likely responsible for the clinical presentation?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3253153",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30551,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. B) Quinolinate phosphoribosyl transferase</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The patient presents with classic signs of pellagra: chronic diarrhea and dermatitis (dry, scaly skin lesions around the neck, likely \"Casal's necklace\"). While pellagra is classically associated with maize (corn) consumption, it can also occur in populations whose staple diet is sorghum (jowar).</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Sorghum contains high quantities of leucine. Excess leucine inhibits quinolinate phosphoribosyl transferase (QPRT), a key enzyme in the conversion pathway from tryptophan to nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+). This inhibition leads to decreased synthesis of niacin (vitamin B3) from tryptophan, resulting in niacin deficiency and the development of pellagra (\"leucine pellagra\").</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Other Options</strong>:</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A. Transaminase</strong>: These enzymes (such as ALT and AST) are involved in amino acid metabolism through transferring amino groups. They are not specifically involved in the tryptophan-to-niacin pathway and their inhibition would not explain the clinical presentation of pellagra.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Quinolinate phosphoribosyl transferase</strong>: Correct - This enzyme catalyzes the conversion of quinolinic acid to nicotinic acid mononucleotide in the pathway from tryptophan to NAD+. Its inhibition by excess leucine in sorghum leads to niacin deficiency manifestations.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Histidase</strong>: This enzyme converts histidine to urocanic acid in histidine metabolism. Histidase deficiency causes histidinemia, characterized by elevated histidine levels and symptoms like speech delay and developmental issues, not pellagra.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D. Tryptophan pyrrolase (now commonly called tryptophan dioxygenase)</strong>: This enzyme catalyzes the first step in tryptophan catabolism, converting tryptophan to N-formylkynurenine. While involved in the tryptophan pathway, its inhibition is not specifically associated with the leucine-induced pellagra seen in sorghum consumption.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Educational objective:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Pellagra is a disease caused by niacin (vitamin B3) deficiency, characterized by the \"4 Ds\": dermatitis, diarrhea, dementia, and death if untreated. While commonly associated with maize-based diets, \"leucine pellagra\" can develop in populations consuming sorghum as a staple food due to leucine's inhibition of QPRT, blocking the endogenous synthesis of niacin from tryptophan. This case highlights the importance of understanding dietary factors that can interfere with specific metabolic pathways.</span></p>",
