      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In a discussion on metabolic pathways, a focus is placed on the role of vitamins as coenzymes in cellular respiration. Which vitamin, when converted into its coenzyme form, serves as a major electron acceptor that facilitates the oxidation of numerous substrates in metabolic pathways?</span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5391585",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30550,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Ans. B)</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Niacin</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD<sup>+</sup>)</strong> is the functional coenzyme <strong>derivative of niacin </strong>and is the <strong>major electron</strong> acceptor in the <strong>oxidation </strong>of molecules, generating <strong>NADH,</strong> which is the <strong>major electron donor</strong> for<strong> reduction reactions.</strong> When <strong>concentrated</strong>, <strong>both</strong> have a<strong> yellow color</strong> due to the<strong> riboflavin</strong> they contain. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Both </strong>function as <strong>prosthetic groups </strong>of <strong>oxidation-reduction enzymes </strong>or <strong>flavoproteins. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Flavoproteins </strong>are <strong>active </strong>in selected <strong>oxidation </strong>reactions and in <strong>electron transport</strong>, but they <strong>do not </strong>have the <strong>ubiquitous role of NAD<sup>+</sup>.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Vitamin B<sub>6</sub>:&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">It acts as <strong>co-enzyme </strong>for many reactions in <strong>amino acid </strong>metabolism such as <strong>methionine and cysteine </strong>metabolism, <strong>decarboxylation </strong>reactions of <strong>amino acids</strong>, <strong>Transamination </strong>etc.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Riboflavin:&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Vitamin B<sub>2</sub> </strong>functions in the <strong>coenzyme </strong>forms of <strong>flavin mononucleotide (FMN) </strong>or <strong>flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD).</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Thiamine:&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Vitamin B<sub>1</sub> occurs functionally as <strong>thiamine pyrophosphate </strong>and is a <strong>coenzyme </strong>for enzymes such as<strong> pyruvate dehydrogenase</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational objective: </span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Niacin</strong>, in <strong>its coenzyme </strong>forms <strong>NAD+ (Nicotinamide Adenine Dinucleotide) and NADP+ (Nicotinamide Adenine Dinucleotide Phosphate), </strong>acts as a <strong>major electron acceptor </strong>in numerous <strong>oxidation-reduction </strong>reactions throughout <strong>cellular metabolism. </strong>These <strong>coenzymes </strong>are involved in <strong>critical pathways </strong>like <strong>glycolysis, the Krebs cycle</strong>, and the <strong>electron transport chain</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: DM Vasudevan&nbsp; 9/e: p 480</span></strong></span></span></p>",
